[{"id":29489,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$80 \\%$","$87 \\%$","$90 \\%$","$97 \\%$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}(\\ell)+\\frac{3}{2} \\mathrm{O}_2(\\mathrm{~g}) \\rightarrow \\mathrm{CO}_2(\\mathrm{~g})+2 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}(\\ell) \\quad \\Delta \\mathrm{H}=-726 \\mathrm{~kJ} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}\n$$\nAlso $\\Delta \\mathrm{G}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0 \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}(\\ell)=-166.2 \\mathrm{~kJ} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{G}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0 \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}(\\ell)=-237.2 \\mathrm{~kJ} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\\\\n& \\Delta \\mathrm{G}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0 \\mathrm{CO}_2(\\ell)=-394.4 \\mathrm{~kJ} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \\\\\n& \\because \\Delta \\mathrm{G}=\\Sigma \\Delta \\mathrm{G}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0 \\text { products }-\\Sigma \\Delta \\mathrm{G}_{\\mathrm{f}}^0 \\text { reactants. } \\\\\n& =-394.4-2(237.2)+166.2 \\\\\n& =-702.6 \\mathrm{~kJ} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\text { now Efficiency of fuel cell }=\\frac{\\Delta \\mathrm{G}}{\\Delta \\mathrm{H}} \\times 100 \\\\\n& =\\frac{702.6}{726} \\times 100 \\\\\n& =97 \\%\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":29348,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>One Faraday of electricity means it is equivalent to one mole of electrons charge.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>–</mo></msup><mo>→</mo><mi>Cu</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> Faraday <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mol</mi><mo> </mo><mi>Cu</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> Faraday <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>→</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mol</mi><mo> </mo><mi>Cu</mi></math> deposit</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo> </mo><mi>atom</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>–</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29292,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For weak acids with $\\lambda^{\\infty}Q^- = \\lambda^{\\infty}Z^-$, the molar conductivity is $\\lambda_m = \\alpha \\lambda^{\\infty}$.<br>From $\\lambda_m^Q = \\frac{1}{30}\\lambda_m^Z$, we get $\\alpha_Q = \\frac{\\alpha_Z}{30}$.<br>Using $K_a = \\alpha^2 C$ for weak acids: $K_a(HQ) = \\alpha_Q^2 \\times 0.18 = \\frac{\\alpha_Z^2 \\times 0.18}{900}$ and $K_a(HZ) = \\alpha_Z^2 \\times 0.02$.<br>Therefore $\\frac{K_a(HZ)}{K_a(HQ)} = \\frac{0.02 \\times 900}{0.18} = 100$.<br>Thus $pK_a(HQ) - pK_a(HZ) = \\log(100) = 2$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29366,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The concentrations of the ions can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>Ksp</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Specific</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>conductance</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Molarity</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>Sm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>6000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>Sm</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Br</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.