/www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>13039</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29342,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>→</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p>Electricity required to oxidise <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>mol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo> </mo><mtext>to</mtext><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mn>96500</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>mole <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math>-factor <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mn>96500</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mn>96500</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>96500</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>93</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>5</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29414,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>From Kohlrausch&#39;s law</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msubsup><mi>&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><msub><mi>BaCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>&#923;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msubsup><mo>(</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>280</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>860</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>426</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>288</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Scm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29463,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["Corrosion of iron can be minimised by forming a contact with another metal with a higher reduction potential","Iron corrodes in oxygen-free water","Corrosion of iron can be minimised by forming an impermeable barrier at its surface","Iron corrodes more rapidly in salt water because its electrochemical potential is higher"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Corrosion of iron can be minimised by forming a contact with another metal with a lower&nbsp;reduction potential. Corrosion of iron can be minimised by forming an impermeable barrier at its surface.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29335,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{M}+\\mathrm{X} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{M}^{2+}+\\mathrm{X}^{2-}\\) is a spontaneous reaction","\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}=0.80 \\mathrm{~V}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}=-0.80 \\mathrm{~V}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{M}^{2+}+\\mathrm{X}^{2-} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{M}+\\mathrm{X}\\) is a spontaneous reaction"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{M} \\mid \\mathrm{M}^{+2} \\| \\mathrm{X} / \\mathrm{X}^{2-} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{cell}}^{\\mathrm{o}}=\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{M} / \\mathrm{M}^{+2}}^{\\mathrm{o}}+\\mathrm{E}_{\\mathrm{X} / \\mathrm{X}^{-2}}^{\\mathrm{o}} \\\\\n& =-0.46+0.34=-0.12 \\mathrm{~V}\n\\end{aligned}$<br />As $\\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}^{\\mathrm{o}}$ is negative so anode becomes cathode and cathode become anode. Spontaneous reaction will be $\\mathrm{M}^{+2}+\\mathrm{X}^{2-} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{M}+\\mathrm{X}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29340,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["\\(10^{-7}\\)","0.5","1","\\(10^{-14}\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & 2 \\mathrm{e}^{-}+2 \\mathrm{H}^{+}(\\mathrm{aq}) \\rightarrow \\mathrm{H}_2(\\mathrm{~g}) \\\\ & \\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{E}^{\\circ}-\\frac{0.059}{\\mathrm{n}} \\log \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{H}_2}}{\\left[\\mathrm{H}^{+}\\right]^2} \\\\ & 0=0-\\frac{0.059}{2} \\log \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{H}_2}}{\\left(10^{-7}\\right)^2} \\\\ & \\log \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{H}_2}}{\\left(10^{-7}\\right)^2}=0 \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{H}_2}}{10^{-14}}=1 \\\\ & \\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{H}_2}=10^{-14} \\text { bar }\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29468,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mn>127</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>","<math><mn>63.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cu</mi></math></p><p>2 Faraday charge deposits 1 mol of Cu, or</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Equivalents</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>Cu</mo></math><br /><br />Mass of Cu deposited<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>63</mn><mo>.5</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29324,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":2,"solution":"Statement I :\nCorrosion is an example of electrochemical phenomenon\n\nIn which pure metal act as anode and impure metal (rusted metal) act as cathode.\n\nStatement II :\nCorrosion is more favourable in acid medium than alkaline so rate of corrosion is high is acid medium then alkaline.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29481,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["Fe (Z = 26)","Co (Z = 27)","Cr (Z = 24)","Mn (Z = 25)"],"answer":1,"solution":"Species having the highest&nbsp;reduction potential i.e., tendency to undergo reduction by gain of electron. SRP value increases from left to right in the period for the d-block elements.<br /><math><mrow><msup><mi> M</mi> <mrow> <mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><msup> <mi>e</mi> <mo>&#8722;</mo> </msup> <mo>&#8594;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msup> <mi>M</mi> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mspace></mspace><mrow><mn>2</mn><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mtext>Fe</mtext><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>/</mo><msup><mtext>Fe</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>6</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>7</mn><mn>7</mn><mtext>&#160;volt</mtext></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mspace></mspace><mrow><mn>2</mn><mn>7</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mtext>Co</mtext><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>/</mo><msup><mtext>Co</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>7</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>9</mn><mn>7</mn><mtext>&#160;volt</mtext></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mspace></mspace><mrow><mn>2</mn><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mtext>Cr</mtext><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>/</mo><msup><mtext>Cr</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>4</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>0</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>4</mn><mtext>&#160;volt</mtext></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mspace></mspace><mrow><mn>2</mn><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mtext>Mn</mtext><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>/</mo><msup><mtext>Mn</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mtext>s</mtext><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>3</mn><msup><mtext>d</mtext><mn>5</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext>.</mtext><mn>5</mn><mn>7</mn><mtext>&#160;volt</mtext></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math><br /><br />Highest reduction potential means strong oxidising agent, i.e. undergoing reduction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Co</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#8594;</mo><msup><mi>Co</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math><span style=\"font-size: 10.8333px;\">.</span>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29478,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$0.3892 \\mathrm{~g}$","$0.2938 \\mathrm{~g}$","$0.2398 \\mathrm{~g}$","$0.3928 \\mathrm{~g}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{W}=\\mathrm{Zit}$\nwhere $\\mathrm{Z}$ = Electrochemical equivalent\nEq. wt. of copper $=\\frac{63}{2}=31.5$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{Z}=\\frac{31.5}{96500} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{~W}=\\mathrm{Zit}=\\frac{31.5}{96500} \\times 1.5 \\times 10 \\times 60=0.2938 \\mathrm{~g}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29283,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$\\dfrac{10^6 x^2}{\\alpha^2(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}$","$\\dfrac{x^2}{(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}$","$\\dfrac{\\alpha^2(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}{10^6 x^2}$","$\\dfrac{x^2}{(x_1 + x_2 + 2x_3)^2}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Using Kohlrausch's law of independent migration of ions, the limiting molar conductivity of $\\text{BaSO}_4$ is given by:<br><br>$\\Lambda^{\\circ}_m(\\text{BaSO}_4) = \\Lambda^{\\circ}_m(\\text{BaCl}_2) + \\Lambda^{\\circ}_m(\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4) - 2\\Lambda^{\\circ}_m(\\text{HCl})$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$\\Lambda^{\\circ}_m(\\text{BaSO}_4) = x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3$<br><br>For a sparingly soluble salt, the solubility $S$ (in mol L$^{-1}$) is related to its conductivity $\\kappa$ (in S cm$^{-1}$) and molar conductivity $\\Lambda_m$ (in S cm$^2$ mol$^{-1}$) by the relation:<br><br>$\\Lambda_m = \\dfrac{\\kappa \\times 1000}{S}$<br><br>Given that $\\kappa = x$ and $\\Lambda_m = \\Lambda^{\\circ}_m$ (which implies complete dissociation, meaning the degree of dissociation $\\alpha = 1$), we get:<br><br>$S = \\dfrac{1000 x}{x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3}$<br><br>The solubility product $K_{sp}$ for $\\text{BaSO}_4$ (which dissociates into $\\text{Ba}^{2+}$ and $\\text{SO}_4^{2-}$) is:<br><br>$K_{sp} = S^2 = \\left( \\dfrac{1000 x}{x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3} \\right)^2 = \\dfrac{10^6 x^2}{(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}$<br><br>Since $\\alpha = 1$, this expression is equivalent to $\\dfrac{10^6 x^2}{\\alpha^2(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}$.<br><br>Answer: $\\dfrac{10^6 x^2}{\\alpha^2(x_1 + x_2 - 2x_3)^2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29448,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Ag}^{+} / \\mathrm{Ag}$","$\\mathrm{Fe}^{3+} / \\mathrm{Fe}^{2+}$","$\\mathrm{Au}^{3+} / \\mathrm{Au}$","$\\mathrm{Fe}^{2+} / \\mathrm{Fe}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{Zn}+2 \\mathrm{Ag}^{+} \\longrightarrow 2 \\mathrm{Ag}+\\mathrm{Zn}^{2+}\\left(n=2 e^{-}\\right)$\r\n\r\n$=0.80-(-0.76)=1.56 \\mathrm{~V}$ for $2 e$\r\n\r\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{E}_{\\text {cell }}^{\\circ}$ for $1 e^{-}=\\frac{1.56}{2}=0.78 \\mathrm{~V}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29368,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given,<br />Resistivity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mi>&#937;cm</mi></math></p><p>Molarity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math></p><p>Thus, Molar conductivity of electrolyte&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></msub></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>mol</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29403,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(iv), (d)-(ii)","(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(ii), (d)-(iv)","(a)-(iii), (b)-(iv), (c)-(i), (d)-(ii)","(a)-(ii), (b)-(i), (c)-(iii), (d)-(iv)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Cell constant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Conductivity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi><mi>RA</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;</p><p>Molar Conductivity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mtext>&#160;Molarity&#160;</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>mol</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Degree of dissociation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math> Number of mole dissociated out of one mole, hence, it is dimensionless.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29472,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In complete cation electrolysis at cathode, the species having higher reduction potential is preferably reduced at cathode<br /><math> <mrow> <msubsup> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>C</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msubsup> <mo>&#62;</mo> <msubsup> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>B</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msubsup> <mo>&#62;</mo> <msubsup> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>D</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msubsup> <mo>&#62;</mo> <msubsup> <mtext>E</mtext> <mtext>A</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math><br />Hence,&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br />will be the preference of deposition of these metals on competing.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":29285,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The conductivity (specific conductance), $\\kappa$, is given by the product of conductance and cell constant:<br><br>$\\kappa = G \\times G^*$<br><br>$\\kappa = 1.9 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ S} \\times 1.3 \\text{ cm}^{-1} = 2.47 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ S cm}^{-1}$<br><br>The molar conductivity, $\\Lambda_m$, is related to the conductivity and molarity $C$ by the formula:<br><br>$\\Lambda_m = \\dfrac{\\kappa \\times 1000}{C}$<br><br>Substituting the given values:<br><br>$123.5 = \\dfrac{2.47 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 1000}{C}$<br><br>$123.5 = \\dfrac{2.47}{C}$<br><br>$C = \\dfrac{2.47}{123.5} = 0.02 \\text{ mol L}^{-1}$<br><br>Molarity $C$ can also be expressed in terms of mass percentage $x$ (w/w), density $d$, and molar mass $M$:<br><br>$C = \\dfrac{x \\times d \\times 10}{M}$<br><br>Substituting the known values ($d = 1.0 \\text{ g mL}^{-1}$, $M = 75 \\text{ g mol}^{-1}$):<br><br>$0.02 = \\dfrac{x \\times 1.0 \\times 10}{75}$<br><br>$1.5 = 10x$<br><br>$x = 0.15$<br><br>Expressing $x$ in the required format:<br><br>$x = 15 \\times 10^{-2}$<br><br>The value is $15$.<br><br>Answer: $15$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29476,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>2.69 V</mtext> </mrow> </math> ; the reaction will not occur","<math> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>2.69 V</mtext> </mrow> </math> ; the reaction will occur","<math> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>0.33 V</mtext> </mrow> </math> ; the reaction will not occur","<math> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>0.33 V</mtext> </mrow> </math> ; the reaction will occur"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mrow><mo>&#916;</mo> <msup> <mtext>G</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>nF</mtext><msup> <mtext>E</mtext> <mo>&#8728;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> <mo>&#8594;</mo> <mtext>Mn</mtext> </mrow> </math>&nbsp; &nbsp;........... (1)<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>G</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mtext>F</mtext> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>1.18</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow><mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>2.36 F</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <msup> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> <mo>&#8594;</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msup> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math>&nbsp; &nbsp;....... (2)<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#916;</mo><mtext>G</mtext><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>F</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mtext>+1.51</mtext></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mtext>3.02 F</mtext></math><br /><br />(1) - (2)<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <msup> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>&#8594;</mo> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msup> <mtext>Mn</mtext> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>G</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>2.36F</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"><mrow>&#160;<mtext>3.02F</mtext> </mrow> </mfenced> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>5.38 F</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>G</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mtext>F</mtext> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mtext>E</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mtext>E</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>5.38F</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mtext>F</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mo>-</mo> <mtext>2.69 V</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br />We know that when E<sub>cell</sub> &lt; 0, cell is non-spontaneous.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29346,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["B, C and E only","A, B, C, D and E","A, B, C and D only","B, D and E only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>A rechargeable nickel-cadmium cell in a jelly roll arrangement and separated by a layer soaked in moist sodium or potassium hydroxide. Another important secondary cell is the nickel-cadmium cell which has longer life than the lead storage cell but more expensive to manufacture. We shall not go into details of working of the cell and the electrode reactions during charging and discharging. The overall reaction during discharge is.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cd</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Ni</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>CdO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Ni</mi><msub><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mfenced></msub></math></p><p>The primary cell Leclanché cell cell is represented as </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>|</mo><msup><mi>Zn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>∥</mo><msub><mi>MnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>|</mo><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>|</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p>Mn, Ni and Cd metals used in battery industries.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29451,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Electrochemistry","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>160</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>80</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>160</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>320</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>G</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><msup><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>Q</mi></math><br />At equilibrium <math><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>G</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi></math><br /><math><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><msup><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow